## Summary

Re-ingesting an already-ingested memory-wiki source destroys the user's notes. `openclaw wiki ingest <path>` (and the gateway `wiki` ingest tool) write each source page with a `## Notes` block delimited by `<!-- openclaw:human:start -->` / `<!-- openclaw:human:end -->` markers that the user is meant to edit. When the same source is ingested again (same title, so same slug and same `sources/<slug>.md` path), the page is regenerated with an empty Notes block and overwritten, silently dropping anything the user wrote inside the human-managed block.

This contradicts the documented contract in `docs/plugins/memory-wiki.md:129`: "Managed content stays inside generated blocks. Human note blocks are preserved."

## Root cause

`extensions/memory-wiki/src/ingest.ts` rebuilds the full page body with a hardcoded empty human block and writes it unconditionally, never reading the existing page:

```ts
// before
      "## Notes",
      "<!-- openclaw:human:start -->",
      "<!-- openclaw:human:end -->",
      "",
    ].join("\n"),
  });

  await fs.writeFile(pagePath, markdown, "utf8");
```

The sibling write paths already preserve the human block by reading the existing page first: synthesis (`apply.ts` `buildSynthesisBody` threads `originalBody` through `replaceManagedMarkdownBlock`) and the ChatGPT importer (`chatgpt-import.ts` `preserveExistingPageBlocks` re-injects the existing human block). Ingest was the lone writer that skipped this step.

## Fix

When the page already exists, read it and re-inject its existing human Notes block into the freshly rendered markdown before writing. The helper lives next to the existing human-block markers in `markdown.ts`:

```ts
// after - markdown.ts
const SOURCE_CONTENT_HEADING = "\n## Content\n";

function afterSourceContentFence(page: string): number {
  const headingIndex = page.indexOf(SOURCE_CONTENT_HEADING);
  if (headingIndex === -1) {
    return 0;
  }
  const fenceLineStart = headingIndex + SOURCE_CONTENT_HEADING.length;
  const fence = /^`+/.exec(page.slice(fenceLineStart))?.[0];
  if (!fence) {
    return fenceLineStart;
  }
  const closeIndex = page.indexOf(`\n${fence}`, fenceLineStart + fence.length);
  if (closeIndex === -1) {
    return fenceLineStart;
  }
  return closeIndex + fence.length + 1;
}

function findNotesHumanBlock(page: string): { start: number; end: number } | null {
  const searchFrom = afterSourceContentFence(page);
  const start = page.indexOf(HUMAN_START_MARKER, searchFrom);
  if (start === -1) {
    return null;
  }
  const endMarker = page.lastIndexOf(HUMAN_END_MARKER);
  if (endMarker < start) {
    return null;
  }
  return { start, end: endMarker + HUMAN_END_MARKER.length };
}

export function preserveHumanNotesBlock(rendered: string, existing: string): string {
  const existingBlock = findNotesHumanBlock(existing);
  const renderedBlock = findNotesHumanBlock(rendered);
  if (!existingBlock || !renderedBlock) {
    return rendered;
  }
  return (
    rendered.slice(0, renderedBlock.start) +
    existing.slice(existingBlock.start, existingBlock.end) +
    rendered.slice(renderedBlock.end)
  );
}
```

```ts
// after - ingest.ts
  const existing = created ? "" : await fs.readFile(pagePath, "utf8").catch(() => "");
  await fs.writeFile(
    pagePath,
    existing ? preserveHumanNotesBlock(markdown, existing) : markdown,
    "utf8",
  );
```

The only untrusted region on the page is the source text, which is fenced inside `## Content`. `renderMarkdownFence` chooses a fence delimiter strictly longer than any backtick run in the content, so the source can never close its own fence early; the rest of the page (the `## Notes` block, then the generated `## Related` block, which carries only `openclaw:wiki:related` markers) is structurally trusted. The helper scans for the human block only after that fence closes, taking the first start marker and the last end marker. The whole Notes block is therefore preserved verbatim even when the source content or the user's own note text contains the human marker comments or Markdown headings. New page creation is unchanged (`created` short-circuits the read), and the freshly generated source content is still written; only the human block is carried forward.

## Why this is the right boundary

`ingestMemoryWikiSource` is the single function behind both the `wiki ingest` CLI command (`cli.ts:588`) and the gateway ingest tool, so fixing it covers both entry points. The human-block markers and detection already live in `markdown.ts`, so the preserve helper is colocated with the contract it protects. The two sibling writers (synthesis, ChatGPT import) already preserve the block, so no other surface needs changing; this change brings ingest in line with them.

## Verification

- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/memory-wiki/src/ingest-human-notes.test.ts` (four cases pass with the patch): plain re-ingest, human markers inside the source content, a pasted human start marker inside the note, and a `## Notes` heading inside the note. Each later case fails on the correspondingly weaker matcher and passes once the block is anchored past the `## Content` fence.
- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/memory-wiki/src/ingest.test.ts` (existing create-path assertion unchanged) passes.
- `node scripts/run-oxlint.mjs` and `oxfmt --check` clean on the three changed files.
- tsgo core typecheck clean.

## Real behavior proof

Behavior addressed: re-ingesting the same memory-wiki source wiped user notes stored in the page's human-managed `## Notes` block; with the patch the notes survive while the regenerated source content is still updated, including when the source content or the note text itself contains the human marker comments or a Markdown heading.
Real environment tested: drove the real `ingestMemoryWikiSource` runtime function (the exact function behind `wiki ingest` and the gateway ingest tool) against a real on-disk vault on pristine base `4c736df975` and on the patched head `e6c048af30`, with identical inputs. Four scenarios: plain re-ingest; source content that itself contains the human markers; note text that contains a pasted human start marker; note text that contains a Markdown heading. Everything stayed real (real vault on disk, real render/write path); nothing was stubbed.
Exact steps or command run after this patch: for each scenario, ingest the source, edit the page Notes block to add a note, overwrite the source file, re-ingest the same path, then read the page back from disk.
Evidence after fix:
```
# BEFORE (pristine base 4c736df975)
[scenario 1: plain re-ingest]
updated source content present: true
user note present after re-ingest: false
[scenario 2: re-ingest where source content itself contains the human markers]
source content INJECTED FROM SOURCE present: true
Notes block keeps user note: false
Notes block free of source content: true
[scenario 3: re-ingest where the note text itself contains a marker comment]
note kept before pasted marker (EARLY NOTE): false
note kept after pasted marker (LATE NOTE): false
[scenario 4: re-ingest where the note text contains a Markdown heading]
note kept above pasted heading (NOTE TOP): false
note kept below pasted heading (NOTE BOTTOM): false

# AFTER (this patch e6c048af30, identical inputs)
[scenario 1: plain re-ingest]
updated source content present: true
user note present after re-ingest: true
[scenario 2: re-ingest where source content itself contains the human markers]
source content INJECTED FROM SOURCE present: true
Notes block keeps user note: true
Notes block free of source content: true
[scenario 3: re-ingest where the note text itself contains a marker comment]
note kept before pasted marker (EARLY NOTE): true
note kept after pasted marker (LATE NOTE): true
[scenario 4: re-ingest where the note text contains a Markdown heading]
note kept above pasted heading (NOTE TOP): true
note kept below pasted heading (NOTE BOTTOM): true
```
Observed result after fix: the re-ingested page keeps the user's note inside the Notes block while still showing the updated source content; on pristine base every note is gone. The note survives even when the source content contains the markers, when the note text contains a pasted start marker, and when the note text contains a `## Notes` heading.
What was not tested: no live network or provider request is involved in ingest; full repo build not run.
